name: Nikhil Chinapa
text: I‚Äôm trying to find another article I read over a year ago from a survey in Australia, where young girls who took the survey, thought that women in porn films were how THEY themselves were expected to behave with their (first) boyfriends.

name: Nikhil Chinapa
text:
There is no concept of consent in porn. The woman is usually shown as weak and subservient. Men are shown as powerful and dominating. 

This kind of content if viewed in your early teens (or younger), could dramatically alter your perception of real relationships.

name: Nikhil Chinapa
text:
We understand the need for sex-education but with the internet becoming easily available across the world and with it, adult sites too - this ‚Äúporn education‚Äù is a serious matter. 

Kids could think that the way actors ACT in adult films, is the way REAL-LIFE relationships work.

name: Nikhil Chinapa
text:
If you‚Äôre a parent of a young child, please watch this. It may sound like a radical idea but we need to educate children about the difference between porn and real life. 

The New Zealand porn ad designed to protect children https://t.co/wBOeOf7Nkk

name: Nikhil Chinapa
text: @nis_swiss I‚Äôm sure it‚Äôs going to take a few months to even put protocols in place and vet them. I meant after those systems and assurances were in place ..and those systems and assurances have been scrutinised and examined by the general public.

name: Nikhil Chinapa
Nikhil Chinapa
text:
Here‚Äôs World Rugby trying to figure things out. https://t.co/SqPvVFBVWO

The gig industry needs to start thinking too. Not so much to get back to ‚Äúpartying‚Äù but because thousands of livelihoods and household kitchens depend on these events. https://t.co/4TP6R9jV0A

name: Nikhil Chinapa
text:
@greyoceanblues H&S protocols for all the verticals in an event. From box office to bogs, bars to backstage. 

Everyone gets screened and there‚Äôs a dedicated team to do it. A new department needs to be set up, with their own protocols which everyone has to adhere to.

name: Nikhil Chinapa
text: @greyoceanblues That wouldn‚Äôt work. Everyone gets to buy. You have to figure out access control protocol for everyone at site. Fans, crew, staff.. the whole circus. It‚Äôs a massive undertaking but it‚Äôs possible.

name: Nikhil Chinapa
Nikhil Chinapa
text: @greyoceanblues You‚Äôd need to. Your need to offer ‚Äúno questions asked‚Äù refunds for ticket holders who don‚Äôt come because you‚Äôd be asking them to be responsible and not show up, if they felt unwell.

name: Nikhil Chinapa
text:
@greyoceanblues Also sanitisation tunnels could create a false sense of security, leading to risky behaviour. 

Kinda like how when seatbelts were first introduced, accident cases went up. People felt safe/invincible wearing seat belts.

name: Nikhil Chinapa
text: @greyoceanblues Won‚Äôt help. An infected person carries the virus in their lungs. Sanitisation is for the most part, superficial.

name: Nikhil Chinapa
text:
China + US have approx 22 million borewells, COMBINED.  

India has between 33-35 MILLION of them. If any of you doubt how bad our groundwater situation is and has a friend who farms, don‚Äôt believe me, ask them.

name: Nikhil Chinapa
text:
From 2012 - 2020, India‚Äôs groundwater consumption has increased, not decreased. Mass migration to cities, higher agricultural output and farming have all increased consumption.

Any idiot can see that, but Twitter has a few special ones who don‚Äôt.

name: Nikhil Chinapa
text:
That‚Äôs it‚Äôs a lot worse now. That most of our rivers don‚Äôt reach the sea because the groundwater that feeds them is so severely depleted. 

The Cauvery river is saline 25KM inland! The sea has come in 25KM because the river doesn‚Äôt have enough water 2 reach the ocean. @zenrainman https://t.co/RBt9IuhfJg

name: Nikhil Chinapa
text:
Get in early on each day. We‚Äôve got loads of shaded areas and a selection of specially curated food (and food trucks!) 

It really dampens your festival experience if you get in late, after being stuck in traffic, stuck in parking and then stuck in frisking queues. @Vh1Supersonic https://t.co/UUDr01E5YD

name: Nikhil Chinapa
text:
@starhopp3r Providing free water at an event of this scale and in India, is a huge challenge. Many international festivals that do this, have potable tap water. You can drink straight from the tap. 

They connect 20 taps to a regular city water line, which is how I‚Äôve  seen them do it.

name: Nikhil Chinapa
text:
@starhopp3r Will take your points about the medical staff‚Äôs behaviour on board and discuss with our health and safety team. 

Water points will tend to be crowded - it‚Äôs a logistics issue. We have increased the number of stations this year but that said, I still expect them to be crowded.

name: Nikhil Chinapa
text:
I have no idea which festivals you‚Äôve been to, but our medical facilities are run by highly trained professionals and are free of cost.  

Free water is located at designated areas through the festival and is dispensed in cups. You can also purchase chilled water bottles at bars. https://t.co/2R2Mj7ZJGz

name: Nikhil Chinapa
text: @virsanghvi Also from a topography / human psyche POV, you can‚Äôt beat the Maldives. The islands are ridiculously pretty and every sunset is a jaw-dropping memory (I prefer sunrises there though). Goa can‚Äôt compete with that level of idyllic.

name: Nikhil Chinapa
text:
@virsanghvi I will agree with the points you‚Äôve made about us having got the vision for Goa wrong (or not having had one at all). 

The Maldives on the other hand built better resorts but has had all that tourism money flow OUT of the country (discussion for another time)

name: Nikhil Chinapa
text:
@virsanghvi The cheaper options in the Maldives are all on local islands. I love them BTW - their called ‚Äúguest houses‚Äù and typically have 10-20 rooms. All newly built with proper beds, toilets, ACs etc. I stay in them when I go diving there. 

There are no cheap stand-alones I‚Äôm aware of.

name: Nikhil Chinapa
text:
@virsanghvi You‚Äôve also got to bear in mind that resorts in the Maldives set up on a sliver of land. They have to set up their own electricity, water desalination, waste management AND house their staff on the same island. 

They have no option but to do high-end hotels with this scenario.

name: Nikhil Chinapa
text:
@virsanghvi @KRaviShankar16 Less expensive than the Taj Aguada? I find that hard to believe. Luxury brand hotels aside, for years I‚Äôd stayed in Goa at rooms that cost ‚Çπ200-500 a night (in peak season December). 

The cheapest rooms in the Maldives came in at around $150 - before tax.

name: Nikhil Chinapa
text:
@virsanghvi Umm, Vir I know you travel more than I do but I‚Äôve been going to the Maldives for 15 years and Goa for almost 30. 

Goa‚Äôs always been a budget destination- for hippies and Indian tourists while Maldives‚Äô budget hotels (guesthouses) were introduced by President Nasheed in 2009.

text: @anantaij I stand corrected. Perhaps you should ask your family about the unwritten rule about officers in uniform and political comments.

text: If you disagree, then imagine what stops the army from commenting on foreign policy, immigration, other world leaders, the economy, demonetisation, the arrest of political rivals by the state, communalism, banking policy and NPAs, black money in Switzerland.. etc etc
